## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests, 0 real verifications.** This suite is a textbook **coverage-touching** pattern — every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called (achieving that 95% coverage number), but almost nothing is actually asserted. Bugs in price calculation, CSV formatting, search logic, and removal would all pass these tests silently.

| Severity | Count |
|----------|-------|
| 🔴 Critical | 7 |
| 🟡 Medium | 3 |
| 🟢 Low | 1 |

---

### 🔴 Critical — Tests Giving False Confidence

#### 1. Coverage-touching (systemic, all 10 tests)

The entire class methodically calls every public method with no meaningful assertions. This is the single dominant problem — 7 of 10 tests have **zero assertions**, and the remaining 3 use only `Assert.IsNotNull`, which is nearly as weak.

#### 2. No assertions — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)

Calls `AddProduct` but never verifies the product was stored.

```csharp
// Before
_catalog.AddProduct(product);

// After
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var stored = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(stored);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", stored.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, stored.Price);
```

#### 3. No assertions — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 33)

Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the price changed. **A bug where `UpdatePrice` silently no-ops would pass.**

```csharp
// After
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
```

#### 4. No assertions — `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 39)

Never verifies the product is gone. A `Delete` that does nothing passes this test.

```csharp
// After
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

#### 5. No assertions — `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)

Calls `GetProductCount()` and discards the result. Doesn't even have `Assert.IsNotNull`.

```csharp
// After
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();
Assert.AreEqual(1, count);
```

#### 6. No assertions — `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 69)

Applies a 10% discount but **never checks the resulting prices**. This is the highest-risk method (arithmetic logic) with zero verification.

```csharp
// After
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
